_exec_summary.SummaryText:
 RMP Off-site Consequence Analysis (OCA) Guidance provides tables for obtaining toxic endpoints and exhibit B-1 of this guidance document provided 0.0087 mg/L as the toxic endpoint for chlorine.

Alternative scenarios
For the alternative scenario, the following assumptions were made:  On a hot day, a one inch diameter flexible line connecting the railcar to the rest of the process has a slow leak (not a complete break) from a 0.125 diameter hole.  The line pressure is assumed to be 180 psig.  A chlorine sensor is located about 5 feet horizontally from the rail car and about 15 feet below the hose, and should be activated almost immediately (within less than 1 minute) turning on a visual and audible alarm.  An operator will don a respirator, proceed to the control room, identify the source of the leak and isolate it within 20 minutes.  In those 20 minutes, the RMP*Comp software yields a distance to the toxic endpoint of less than 0.1 mile.

General Accidental Release Prevention Program and Specific Prevention Steps
It is the policy of Kemira to adhere to all applicable federal and state rules and regulations.  Safety depends upon the manner in which Kemira handles chlorine combined with the safety devices inherent in the design of the facility, the safe handling procedures that are employed, and the training of Kemira personnel.  The owners and management of this facility regard employee and public safety as a very serious matter and have taken many precautions to maintain a safe working and public environment.  

Some of these steps include:
Installation of chlorine sensors and alarms;
Installation of an automatic shutoff valve on the railcar unloading system;
Institution of safe operating procedures;
Training employees in safety programs and procedures;
Writing a comprehensive Emergency Response Plan; and
Coordinating with the Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC).

